{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477101","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477101"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:57:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:57:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14178"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14178","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14178"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.45,0.08,0.42,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6861"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107294"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6861","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6861"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14178"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89756"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"682"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"2993"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15631"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17178"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17287"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17346"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17348"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17401"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39185"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44201"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107294","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107294"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 10-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with his parent two hours after falling off his bicycle. He states he hit his abdomen on the handlebar during the fall. He complains of persistent abdominal pain. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears uncomfortable. His pulse rate is 140/min, blood pressure 105/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. His abdomen is tense with tenderness in the left upper quadrant. There is a small circular bruise visible in the same area. The rest of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in providing a definitive diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Abdominal X-ray","Abdominal CT scan","Exploratory laparotomy","Abdominal ultrasound","MRI abdomen"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a classic scenario of a handlebar injury in a child. These injuries can cause significant intra-abdominal organ damage, even when external signs of trauma are minimal. The persistent abdominal pain, tachycardia, and focal tenderness are concerning signs that warrant further investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbdominal CT scan\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step in this scenario. It is the gold standard for evaluating suspected intra-abdominal injuries in paediatric trauma. CT can accurately detect injuries to solid organs (such as the liver, spleen, or pancreas) and hollow viscus injuries that may not be immediately apparent on physical examination. Early detection of these injuries is crucial for appropriate management and to prevent complications. While CT involves exposure to ionising radiation, the benefits of accurate and timely diagnosis in this acute setting outweigh the risks, especially when considering the potential for serious complications if injuries are missed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbdominal ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E, while useful in some scenarios, is less sensitive than CT for detecting solid organ injuries and is particularly limited in detecting hollow viscus injuries. Ultrasound is operator-dependent and may miss subtle injuries, especially in the presence of bowel gas or in cases where the injury is not associated with free fluid. In paediatric trauma, ultrasound is often used as a screening tool but lacks the comprehensive detail provided by CT, making it less suitable as the primary diagnostic tool in this context.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExploratory laparotomy\u003C/strong\u003E is overly invasive as an initial step. It would only be considered if there were signs of peritonitis or hemodynamic instability, which are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbdominal X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically useful for diagnosing intra-abdominal injuries from blunt trauma. It may show free air if there is a perforation, but it is not sensitive for detecting solid organ injuries.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI abdomen\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically used in the acute setting for trauma due to its longer acquisition time and limited availability. It is more useful for detailed imaging of soft tissues in non-urgent scenarios.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter obtaining the CT scan, management would be guided by the findings. Most paediatric solid organ injuries from blunt trauma can be managed conservatively, but early detection is key to appropriate treatment and monitoring.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Handlebar injuries in children can cause significant intra-abdominal organ damage, even without external signs of trauma.","CT abdomen is the gold standard for evaluating suspected intra-abdominal injuries in paediatric trauma.","Persistent abdominal pain, tachycardia, and tenderness are concerning signs that warrant further investigation in paediatric abdominal trauma."],"references":["Royal Children\u2019s Hospital Melbourne. Major paediatric trauma \u2013 the secondary survey. Updated July 2022. Available at: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Major_paediatric_trauma_the_secondary_survey/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89756"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14178"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89756","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89756"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-27T11:54:26+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-27T11:55:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6861"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107294"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"